    <h1>A weekly review template that takes five minutes <em>(The questions I actually answer every Sunday, and the ones I skip)</em></h1>
    
    <p class="lede" style="font-size: 1.25rem; color: var(--ink); line-height: 1.5; margin-bottom: 36px; font-weight: 500;">
      Picture this: It’s late Sunday evening. You sit down with a fresh cup of tea, determined to organize your upcoming week. You open a sprawling, multi-tiered digital workspace workspace filled with complex audit trackers, calendar databases, and a 20-step "Life Assessment Matrix." Twenty minutes in, you are exhausted by the sheer operational overhead of reviewing your own life, close the tab, and go to bed feeling more overwhelmed than when you started.
    </p>

    <img class="hero-img" src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1517842645767-c639042777db?q=80&w=1200" alt="Person hands holding a clean fountain pen over an open minimal calendar layout">
    <div class="img-caption">Stripping down personal reflection to the absolute essentials that actually drive execution.</div>

    <p>We have all fallen victim to over-engineered productivity rituals. The internet is flooded with content recommending that your weekly reflection should look like an institutional financial statement analysis—complete with deep emotional cataloging, habit trend lines, and meticulous goal forecasting. But for student builders, active job seekers, and digital creators, your time is your single most scarce resource. If a review framework feels like an additional corporate chore, you will drop it within a fortnight.</p>

    <p>A personal review should not be an auditing simulation. Its only purpose is to calibrate your direction, clear out mental clutter, and ensure your highest-value actions—like technical dashboard training, outreach to talent acquisition managers, or launching side-project design sheets—take absolute priority. Here is the exact three-question, low-friction review process that takes me less than five minutes every Sunday night.</p>

    <blockquote>
      <p>"The value of a review routine is not found in how much data you collect, but in how fast it transforms into clear, high-intent action."</p>
    </blockquote>

    <h2>The Failure of Over-Engineered Productivity</h2>
    <p>Most productivity frameworks ask you to rate every single aspect of your life on a scale of one to ten, track your hydration percentages, and write lengthy essays on your mindset gaps. If you appreciated the hyper-regimented, administrative exhaustion depicted in <em>Severance</em>, that is exactly what these long audits mimic—a system where managing the documentation takes precedence over performing the actual work.</p>

    <p>When you force yourself through a heavy analytical review every single weekend, you create behavioral friction. When a week goes completely sideways with demanding finals, intense project sprints, or website bugs, your brain will naturally skip the review entirely to protect its energy. A resilient ritual must be brief enough to complete when you are completely wiped out on a Sunday evening.</p>

    <img class="body-img" src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1506784983877-45594efa4cbe?q=80&w=1200" alt="Minimal clean white workspace layout showing a simple pen and a note sheet">
    <div class="img-caption">A simple approach: closing out the old week and defining the immediate target before the noise begins.</div>

    <h2>The 3 Questions I Actually Answer (The 5-Minute Slate)</h2>
    <p>Grab a physical notepad or open a clean document file. Skip the tracking forms and answer these three sharp, high-leverage prompts directly:</p>

    <div class="framework-card">
      <h4>1. What was the absolute biggest win of the past 7 days?</h4>
      <p style="margin-bottom: 12px; font-size: 1rem;"><strong>Why it matters:</strong> As builders, our brains are hardwired to notice what went wrong far faster than identifying what went right. If you don't intentionally record your victories—whether it's cracking a tough financial diagnostic, finalizing an interactive Power BI asset, or typing a clean certification benchmark—you create cognitive fatigue. Claiming the win balances your perspective.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="framework-card">
      <h4>2. Where did I hit the most friction or waste the most bandwidth?</h4>
      <p style="margin-bottom: 12px; font-size: 1rem;"><strong>Why it matters:</strong> This is a cold, objective diagnosis of your calendar. Did you get trapped in a long email rabbit hole? Did an unorganized layout waste two hours of design time? Did you let reactive notifications pull you away from your deep-work windows? Identify the exact leak so you can build a boundary against it next week.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="framework-card">
      <h4>3. What is the single, uncompromised milestone for the upcoming week?</h4>
      <p style="margin-bottom: 12px; font-size: 1rem;"><strong>Why it matters:</strong> This is your keystone priority. If everything else falls apart, what is the one project or outreach goal that makes the week a success? Isolate it, write it down in bold layout style, and lock it into your calendar before other people start scheduling your time.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>The Sprawling Prompts I Intentionally Skip</h2>
    <p>To keep this system under the five-minute threshold, you have to be cutthroat about what you ignore. I completely skip tracking mood fluctuations, rating my life balance circles, logging micro-habits, and drafting open-ended philosophical paragraphs. Those actions are perfectly fine for seasonal deep-dives, but for a weekly operational reset, they simply add weight and slow down your transition into execution mode.</p>

    <blockquote>
      <p>"Simplicity is the ultimate shield against giving up when your schedule meets the chaotic reality of a busy week."</p>
    </blockquote>

    <h2>Protecting Consistency When Your Week is Derailed</h2>
    <p>Let's be completely candid: modern timelines are highly unpredictable. You will encounter weeks where you drop your habits, get overwhelmed by data dashboard bugs, or feel completely unmotivated. When a week goes sideways, your Sunday review becomes your ultimate alignment anchor.</p>
    
    <p>Because this template requires almost zero mental heavy lifting, you can easily maintain it even when your energy is low. Go easy on your expectations during intense career transitions or exam seasons, adjust your workflow variables when traveling, and trust that a minimal, five-minute reality check every Sunday is infinitely more effective than a massive review system you drop after a single week.</p>

    <div class="framework-card" style="border-left: 4px solid var(--moss);">
      <h4>The Execution Shift</h4>
      <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.95rem;">Clear out the over-engineered templates. This Sunday evening, take a clean sheet of paper, ask yourself these three essential questions, outline your singular objective for the week ahead, and start your Monday completely on offense.</p>
